<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>ODPMMin</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Submission from the Department for Communities and Local Government (FDC14)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Programme for Government stated that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">We will promote the radical devolution of power and greater</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> financial autonomy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">…</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. This will include a review of local government finance.’</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">As part of this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">and broad </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">commitment to decentralisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> the Department for Communities and Local Government has:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Devolved significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">functions and funding to the Grea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ter London Authority  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Established and supported Local Enterprise Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> (LEPs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> – bringing together business and local authority leaders across functional economic areas</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Worked with major conurbations to negotiate bespoke City Deals </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Given greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ntrol over resources by removing ringfences on local authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">funding, devolving funding to LEPs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and bringing together health and social care funding</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Rewarded places that deliver growth through the New Homes Bonus and local business rate retention</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Already organisations and individuals affected by these changes are taking advantage of the opportunities they provide to deliver economic growth and tailor services (examples of which are included throughout the remainder of this submission). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">his very significant shift in fiscal and functional responsibilities is still bedding in. As such, any further decentralisation should not be rushed and should always be the subject of careful consideration. The key tests, in addition to legality</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">against </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">which any proposals for future fiscal decentralisation should be measured are: does it support deficit reduction; does it have cross-party support; is it supported by evidence; and; will it have a detrimental effect on the rest of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">UK</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Our overall a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">pproach</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">of the Department to delivering this Government’s commitment to decentralisation has had a number of distinctive themes. These can be summarised as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Devolves appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ly to reflect the contrasting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">strengths</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">different places </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> through a new settlement for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, bespoke City Deals and Growth Deals;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Encourages new partnerships of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">public and private leaders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> through Local Enterprise Partnerships that h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ave been given increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">responsibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, power and funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">to drive growth across their functional economic area;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Devolves substantial funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> –  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">for example </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">£2billion a year from 2015/16 is being devolved to Local Enterprise Partnerships through the Local Growth Fund;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Provides substantial devolved powers and in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">centives that reward growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> – including business rate retention and Enterprise Zones;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Co-designs more integrated and efficient public services </span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">a pooled budget for health and social care services</span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Humanist777BT-LightB; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Clarifies and strengthens local accountability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">– through Accountability System Statements for local authorities and the Greater London Authority and strengthening public accountability in relation to local authority meetings and data</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-72pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The key policies that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> have delivered on these themes are set out below.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">A new settlement for London</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Localism Act (2011) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">devolved significant extra powers to the Mayor of London, conferring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">in the capital for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">housing economic development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Olympic legacy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> This was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">in addition to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">his existing powers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">over transport, planning and the police. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Increasing the Mayor’s powers in this way recognises the very real difference in housing market in the capital.  It also gives responsibility for strategic planning, housing and transport decisions to one individual, thus providing far greater opportunitie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">s for efficient investment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In order to ensure these new functions could be effectively discharged, the Government negotiated an accompanying comprehensive funding settlement for the remainder of the Spending Review period. This funding package is worth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">over £3 billion.  This is in addition to monies it receives from the HO and DfT for policing and transport and the revenue it raises itself through TfL fares, the congestion charge, retained business rates and the council tax precept (in 2013/14 over 50% o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">f the GLA Group’s income is self-generated).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The London Finance Commission established by the Mayor reported in May 2013. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government welcomes the report's contribution to the ongoing public debate on the scope for further decentralisation. However, we</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">stated that we have no current plans to transfer more powers to the Greater London Authority, given </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">vol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ution under the Localism Act described above and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">decentralisation of local government finance through the Local Government Financ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">e Act 2012 (described under the later section on Business Rate reform)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Bespoke City Deals </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Outside of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unlocking Growth in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cities (Dec 2011), the Government set out its intention to agree a series of bespoke city deals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. These were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> designed to give cities the freedoms and flexibilities they need to drive local growth. Each deal is the result of a negotiation and decentralises significant responsibilities. In the 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Wave Government worked with the eight largest cities outside </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> - Liverpool, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Nottingham, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Leeds and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to agree city deals. The first eight deals were concluded in July 2012. The core cities have estimated that the first wave of deals will create </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">175,000 jobs over the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">next 20 years and 37,000 new apprenticeships.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Humnst777 Lt BT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 17.85pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following the success of Wave 1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">City D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eals, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the Government invited a further twenty cities and their wider areas to compete for deals that will see the Government devolve powers in exchange for responsibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for delivering growth locally. Nine deals have been agreed so far, with Preston, Reading &amp; Thames Valley Berkshire, Ipswich, Portsmouth &amp; Southampton, Coventry &amp; Warwickshire, Greater Norwich, Black Country, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Valley</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Hull &amp; Humber. And the remaining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deals will be concluded by early 2014 or transition towards a Local Growth Deal (see the section below for more detail on these). </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Taken together, these deals provide a suite of new freedoms, powers and tools to help cities go for growth. Examples of powe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">rs and incentives include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Economic Investment Funds. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The power to pool multiple funding streams and business rate income into a single investment fund, leverage private sector capital and invest in local priorities – reducing dependence on central government grants (Greater Birmingham and Solihull, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">nd West of Englad, Greater Manchester, Leed City Region, Liverpool City Region and Sheffield City Region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ised Skills funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">A new model of skills funding that will match local contributions (public and private) with national funding to provide a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">skills budget that cities will control to invest in the skills that local businesses need (Sheffield City Region).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Earn Back. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">A new payment by result model that incentivises a city to invest in growth in return for a share of the national tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Manche</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ster</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Localised youth contracts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Local alternatives to the national 16-17 youth contract programme, with cities having the power to design and deliver local models to reduce the number of people not in employment, education or training (Leeds City Region</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, Liverpool, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">).</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Rail devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">: Increasing city control over rail services by devolving greater responsibility for commissioning and managing franchise arrangements for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">local and regional rail services (e.g. Northern Rail). (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and West of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Region, Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Region) </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 14.3pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Devolution of local transport majors funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">: matching local resources with devolved transport budgets so cities have the power and resources to make strategic transport investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">s. (Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Birmingham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and Solihull, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and West of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Leeds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Region, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">City</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Region) </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Gain Share</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: a payment by results mechanism whereby Greater Cambridge will be able to keep a larger proportion of the proceeds of economic growth generated in, and around, the city of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cambridge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Details to be announced in Budget 2014.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Growth Deals and the evolution </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">of Local Enterprise Partnerships</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Throughout England 39 Local Enterprise Partnerships were formed in 2010-11. These partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">are locally owned, business-civic partnerships, tasked with taking the strategic lead for economic growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">own functio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">nal economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. Over the course of this Parliament LEPs have evolved and gained </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">powers, including managing the 24 Enterprise Zones (for more detail on Enterprise Zones see later section).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">A key point in the evolution of LEPs was the Government’s response to Heseltine’s report ‘No Stone Unturned’. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government accepted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">the overwhelming majority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> of the 89 wide-ranging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">recommendations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">and in March </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">announced:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The creation of the Local Growth Fund - £2bn in 2015/16. This will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">allocated through a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">competitive process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">;</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Local Growth Fund will continue to be at least £2 billion a y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ear through the next Parliament</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:26.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">LEPs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">be given the responsibility to decide ho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">w the £5.3 billion EU Structural and Investment Funds for 2014/20 will be spent in their local area.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">LEPs are now developing multi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">year Strategic Economic Plans, which are an opportunity for business and civic leaders to set out the vision, priorities and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> interventions for growth in their areas. The Government will negotiate a Local Growth Deal with each individual LEP on the basis of its Strategic Economic Plan.  Local Growth Deals will enable LEPs to access funding from the Local Growth Fund. However, Gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">owth Deals are not just about securing money they will </span><a name="OLE_LINK1"></a><a name="OLE_LINK2"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">also include</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> greater influence over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">key levers affecting local growth and additional freedom and flexibilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Rewarding growth: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Business Rates Retention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Tax Increment Financing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline"> and Enterprise Z</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">ones</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Business Rate reforms</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In April 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">on the back of the review of local government finance promised in the Coalition Agreement, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the Government introduced the rates retention scheme. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Under the scheme, locally collected business rates are spilt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">between central and local government on a 50/50 basis.  This provides a direct link between business rates growth and the amount of money local authorities have to spend on local people and services and means there is a powerful incentive for local authori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ties to pursue local growth policies.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In setting up the scheme, Government recognised that business rates income was volatile and that the size of the business rates base (and therefore business rates income) varies from authority to authority.  So to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">make the scheme fairer the Government created a number of mechanisms to redistribute resource and build in protections.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Top ups and tariffs were a one off redistribution (of business rates income) across the sector at the start of the scheme and are fixed until the scheme is reset (currently due in 2020) but will be uprated each year by the change in the small business mult</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">iplier.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Where an authority’s business rates income is higher that its baseline funding level (an assessment of spending need), it will pay a levy to Government. This levy is limited to a maximum of 50p in the £. To ensure protection in cases of pronoun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ced volatility where an authority’s business rates income falls by more that 7.5% it will receive a safety net payment from Government - this ensures that an authority will always have 92.5% of its baseline funding level.    Income from the levy funds the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">safety net.  Top up authorities do not pay the levy.    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">These reforms support local authorities to raise additional income in three ways:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Tax Increment Financing</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The business rates retention scheme gives all councils unfettered access to tax increment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> financing by enabling them to retain and borrow again</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">st future business rates.  TIF </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">operates within the rates retention scheme, which means that any growth will be subject to the levy and the reset will apply. Such borrowing can be undertaken entirely at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">local discretion, is within the prudential borrowing regime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and is not subject to central Government monitoring.   </span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33pt; padding-left:3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">New Deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">lopment Deals </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Designed specifically to support large scale infrastructure projects, New Development Deals also offer 100% rates r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">etention for a 25 year period.   Announced as part of the Wave 1 City Deals in July 2012 New Development Deals exist in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> (£92m</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">), Nottingham (£8m) and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> (£33m). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">New Development Deals are supported by £150m funding provided in Budget 2011 t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">o offset the impact upon public sector net debt. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Enterprise Zones  </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The 24 Enterprise Zones are at the centre of our commitment to back business, help local economies grow stronger and keep the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> competitive on the world stage. The Government has transf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ormed the landscape of local economic development, giving local leaders the powers and funds to shape their own economy and keep the benefits locally.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">They </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">are proving a magnet for growing and established businesses that are benefitting from business-frie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ndly measures such as tax incentives, superfast broadband, simple planning rules that make it easier to start building and millions in Government funding for infrastructure.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; line-height:13pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government is investing nearly £700m to support Enterprise Zones and their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Local Enterprise Partnerships to realise their potential as the engine rooms of local economies.  Local areas will benefit from millions of pounds of taxes generated by the businesses in their Enterprise Zone over the next 25 years.  The money, generated t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">hrough the 100% business rate retention scheme, can be reinvested in local businesses, jobs and skills and will provide Local Enterprise Partnerships with a guaranteed funding stream.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Again, no central approval for the borrowing is required</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Enterprise Zon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">es are about delivering long term, sustainable growth based on cutting-edge technology and enterprise. They are creating new centres of excellence in sectors such as pharmaceuticals, automotive and renewable energy that will help nurture skills to meet the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> demands of the new economy. Since their start in April 2012 they have laid down the foundations of their success, attracting 212 businesses and international investment, securing half a billion pounds of private sector investment, building world class bus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">iness facilities and transport links and creating nearly 5,000 jobs.    </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Future plans</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Whilst the Government has no plans to finance further New Development Deals at this point, there are existing commitments to allow 100% retention in:</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.2pt; padding-left:14.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">5 Enterprise Areas in the West of England City Deal area (as announced in the Wave 1 City Deals).  DCLG’s is committed to providing £17m from the unallocated New Development Deals funding.   </span></li><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.2pt; padding-left:14.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Vauxhall Nine Elms development area.  Here the Chancellor has co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">mmitted to allow the GLA to undertake up to £1bn borrowing to deliver the Northern Line Extension.   </span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Enabling Public Service Transformation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Bringing together Health and Wellbeing Funding</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Greater fiscal freedom is supported by removing unnecessary ringf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ences and integrating funding – both of which allow organisations to better control their own budgets and work with their partners. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">In 2015/16 we will be investing £3.8 billion of pooled health and social care funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">, the Better Care Fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. This will suppo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">rt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">local authorities to work more effectively with clinical commissioning groups and other local partners to deliver better outcomes for less money and drive integration. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Pooling of budgets will be at a local level. Every area will have a pooled budget, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">jointly governed by C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">linical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ommissioning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">roup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> (CCGs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and LAs. The balance of spend between health and social care services within areas, will be subject to local decisions and access to the pooled fund will be conditional on agreed plans for transforma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">tion. The content of the plans will be locally agreed and signed-off by local health and wellbeing boards.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">This change can make a substantial difference to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">people quickly.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> Whilst the Fund does not come into full effect until 2015/16, it is essential that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> CCGs and local authorities make progress and build momentum in 2014/15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">. For this reason an extra </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">£200m </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">will be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">transferred to local government from the NHS to support transformation. By taking early action, pressure on the NHS can be reduced faster and mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">re effectively – for example, on unplanned admissions, of which there are more than 2 million for people over 65 (accounting for 68 per cent of hospital emergency bed days, and the use of more than 51,000 acute beds)</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Co-designing services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The four </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Whole</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">-Place Community Budget pilots</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> proved the concept that better outcomes can be delivered for less, by redesigning public services around the needs of users. The over-arching philosophy was that the health of local economies and local places depends on both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">boosting growth and reforming public services to reduce long-term demand and dependency on the state. However, eac</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">h of the pilots also addressed a specific ‘Economy’ theme (worklessness and skills, economic growth and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">infrastructure) – for example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">work an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">d skills looked at local skills mis-match, small business start ups, service re-design for the most complex cases for universal credit, securing employment and the crucial role work and skills plays in developing community resilience.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Public Service T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ransformation Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> is a new way of doing business across central and local government that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> builds on the lessons learnt from the Whole-Place Community Budgets. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">At its core is a team brought together from across government, local government and partner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">agencies with a broad range of capabilities and policy expertise to help places co-design local services; a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ctivity is driven from the bottom up with the Transformation Network providing the support, encouragement and challenge to go further and faster.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Public Service Transformation Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">is working closely with 13 places, including several from within </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Core</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Greater </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manchester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Tri-borough </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(RB Kensington and Chelsea, LB Hammersmith and Fulham, and Westminster City Counc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">il);</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lambeth, Lewisham and  Southwark;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sheffield</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">West London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Barnet, Brent, Ealing, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harrow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Hillingdon and Hounslow); and </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 2.25pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wirral.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The development of this public service transformation approach, in particular the activities and experience of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">the Whole-Place Community Budget pilots, has been favourably reported on by both the Public Accounts Committee</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> and the Communities and Local Government Committee</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">Clarifying and strengthening local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:underline">ccountability arrangements</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Wherever fiscal devolution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> takes place, it is important that appropriate accountability arrangements are in place to protect public funds. This evidence has set out above some of the specific accountability arrangements we have established such as payment by results as part of some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> City Deals. While central oversight of public resources may be appropriate in some cases, this Government firmly believes that accountability to local people is of critical importance.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The Government has therefore taken steps to clarify and strengthen lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">cal accountability arrangements in local government. The Department’s accountability system statement for local government sets out the range of checks and balance on local authorities to provide assurance that they spend their resources properly. For exam</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">ple, all authorities are required to have a Chief Finance Officer who is placed under various legal obligations and all authorities must set a balanced budget every year. This helps our Accounting Officer to account to Parliament for the use of these resou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">rces. There is a separate statement for the Greater London Authority in view of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">’s unique governance and funding arrangements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.68pt; padding-left:5.32pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To strengthen accountability at a local level, the Government has made it clear that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all meetings of an executive, its com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mittees or subcommittees must be held in public except in limited defined circumstances</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. To ensure the public has the information needed to hold elected members to account, we have introduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Code of Recommended Practice for Local Authorities on Data Tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sparency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which recommends that all councils publish a wide range of spending and performance data. We have recently published a revised version of that code, which minister</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> intend to make mandatory. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 2.15pt 5pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">9 January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">For example ensuring compliance with State </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">id rules</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">The second, third and fourth of these tests were established in relation to fiscal decentralisation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> but have broader applicability. They were established</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> by the Secretary of State for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> during the passage of the Scotland Act. The direct quote can be found at </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110621/debtext/110621-0004.htm#11062211001095"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt; text-decoration:none">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110621/debtext/110621-0004.htm#11062211001095</span></a><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">For more information on business rates r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">etention go to: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/266886/LGFS_Guide.pdf</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TIF is a method to use future gains in taxes to subsidize current improvements, which are projected to create the conditions for said gains. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">When an increase in site value and private investment generates an increase in tax revenues, it is the "tax increment."</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> All figures have been rounded.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; letter-spacing:-0.1pt">Older People and Emergency Bed Use – Kings Fund, August 2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">See </span><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmpubacc/472/47202.htm"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:none">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmpubacc/472/47202.htm</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 2.15pt 0pt 0pt; text-al